00:29:11,492 --> 00:29:12,947
to match 100 couples.

484
00:29:13,072 --> 00:29:16,872
We find a man and a woman
you introduced hitting it off, kissing,

485
00:29:17,377 --> 00:29:18,977
and you drag him away.

486
00:29:19,102 --> 00:29:21,382
Have you not been
paying any attention?

487
00:29:21,694 --> 00:29:24,640
Look, I only get credit
for a match if it's true love,

488
00:29:25,037 --> 00:29:27,598
The kind of love
you'd cross oceans to find.

489
00:29:27,766 --> 00:29:30,101
They were very specific
on that point.

490
00:29:30,269 --> 00:29:32,375
Romeo and Juliet counts.

491
00:29:32,500 --> 00:29:34,964
Romeo and the coat
check girl doesn't.

492
00:29:35,128 --> 00:29:35,856
Guys.

493
00:29:37,451 --> 00:29:39,151
- What's up?
- No luck.

494
00:29:40,591 --> 00:29:42,113
All right, on to plan "B".

495
00:29:47,165 --> 00:29:50,979
There are two guys in the alley
trying to drop off a p.a.

496
00:29:51,104 --> 00:29:53,791
They're asking me for a check.
Except I didn't rent a p.a.

497
00:29:53,959 --> 00:29:55,709
Don't you read the paper?

498
00:29:56,832 --> 00:29:58,593
Having a big show here tonight.

499
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:03,300
You should fire him.

500
00:30:04,011 --> 00:30:05,845
What is it with you and strays?

501
00:30:08,735 --> 00:30:11,478
The patient who was given
the single name Jenny Q

502
00:30:11,603 --> 00:30:14,478
suffers from somatoform disorder.

503
00:30:14,830 --> 00:30:18,487
Now specifically she suffered
from conversion disorder representing

504
00:30:18,612 --> 00:30:21,026
a central neurological symptom
such as...

505
00:30:24,360 --> 00:30:25,460
<i>It's Trevor.</i>

506
00:30:26,388 --> 00:30:27,588
<i>Trevor Pierce.</i>

507
00:31:08,065 --> 00:31:09,408
- Big night.
- Yeah.

508
00:31:09,795 --> 00:31:12,328
They all want to know
if this Holly is gonna show up.

509
00:31:16,327 --> 00:31:18,161
Still think I should fire him?

510
00:31:23,848 --> 00:31:25,498
You sure clean up nice.

511
00:31:26,025 --> 00:31:28,177
Am I being stupid?
He's in love with someone else.

512
00:31:28,345 --> 00:31:30,930
You're being proactive.
That's chapter one of my book.

513
00:31:31,098 --> 00:31:34,298
Well, if it isn't the lady
that made it all possible.

514
00:31:34,423 --> 00:31:35,806
These are on the house.

515
00:31:35,931 --> 00:31:38,854
Well, if it isn't "tremor pierced."

516
00:31:50,369 --> 00:31:52,119
Cheers. Thanks very much.

517
00:31:53,147 --> 00:31:54,578
This... this next song

518
00:31:54,746 --> 00:31:56,512
I learned especially for tonight,

519
00:31:56,637 --> 00:31:59,839
and it goes out to somebody
who's spectacularly uncool, but,

520
00:32:00,377 --> 00:32:02,122
that's what I dig about her.

521
00:32:07,020 --> 00:32:08,075
All right!

522
00:32:10,636 --> 00:32:12,159
<i>What I want, you've got</i>

523
00:32:12,284 --> 00:32:14,723
<i>And it might be hard to handle</i>

524
00:32:15,225 --> 00:32:18,936
<i>Like a flame that burns a candle
The candle feeds the flame</i>

525
00:32:19,336 --> 00:32:22,510
A couple of days ago, I felt sorry
for the girl on the Times Square sign,

526
00:32:22,635 --> 00:32:24,525
- and now, I'm jealous of her.
- Don't be.

527
00:32:24,795 --> 00:32:27,736
He's only in love
with the idea of someone else.

528
00:32:27,904 --> 00:32:29,762
<i>Well, well, well, you</i>

529
00:32:32,061 --> 00:32:35,087
<i>You're makin' my dreams come true.</i>

530
00:32:49,843 --> 00:32:51,010
I knew I'd find you.

531
00:33:11,735 --> 00:33:13,490
This is it.
You've got your story!

532
00:33:13,980 --> 00:33:16,237
But I didn't want
to get the story this time, Trevor.

533
00:33:16,362 --> 00:33:18,255
I wanted to be the girl
that got the song,

534
00:33:18,380 --> 00:33:20,279
- and I was this close.
- But, Madelyn...

535
00:33:20,665 --> 00:33:22,475
I tried being bold, Trevor.

536
00:33:23,575 --> 00:33:25,705
I should've stuck with being smart.

537
00:33:36,223 --> 00:33:37,306
I love this place.

538
00:33:37,718 --> 00:33:40,934
All it needs is those little jukeboxes
that they have in the booths, you know?

539
00:33:42,934 --> 00:33:44,866
This is Holly.
Holly, this is a friend of mine.

540
00:33:44,991 --> 00:33:47,805
This is the guy who's responsible for
twisting the fabric of space and time

541
00:33:47,930 --> 00:33:50,361
- and getting us back together.
- A regular Cupid.

542
00:33:50,607 --> 00:33:51,533
Who told you?

543
00:33:51,658 --> 00:33:54,197
We were just talking about
what our first real date should be.

544
00:33:54,322 --> 00:33:57,242
Simple. Red-eye to Vegas.
Elvis impersonator hitches you.

545
00:33:57,410 --> 00:33:58,810
Lifetime of bliss.

546
00:33:59,351 --> 00:34:01,914
- I was thinking a movie.
- You came a long way.

547
00:34:02,082 --> 00:34:04,124
You don't want
to make it dinner and a movie?

548
00:34:04,292 --> 00:34:06,710
I make it a point to clear
my schedule for any man

549
00:34:06,878 --> 00:34:09,294
who puts my name
in lights on Times Square.

550
00:34:09,588 --> 00:34:12,132
Well, how about
a carriage ride through the park?

551
00:34:16,786 --> 00:34:19,556
Oh, my God.
You were serious. I'm so sorry.

552
00:34:19,724 --> 00:34:22,962
Jaded New Yorker completely devoid
of a sense of wonder.

553
00:34:23,087 --> 00:34:25,108
So... What was your reaction

554
00:34:25,233 --> 00:34:27,911
when you saw Dave's picture
in the paper, and you read the story?

555
00:34:28,036 --> 00:34:30,275
My first reaction?
"Who is this guy?"

556
00:34:30,831 --> 00:34:33,042
But I called my sister,
and she reminded me.

557
00:34:33,167 --> 00:34:35,114
I guess I'd sent her
an e-mail that said,

558
00:34:35,282 --> 00:34:37,396
"Finally met a cool guy in Ireland.

559
00:34:37,521 --> 00:34:39,280
"Too bad it was my last day."

560
00:34:39,903 --> 00:34:41,495
You're that cool guy.

561
00:34:44,628 --> 00:34:45,791
Cool is not everything.

562
00:34:57,637 --> 00:34:59,304
- Hello?
<i>- Hi. It's Trevor.</i>

563
00:34:59,872 --> 00:35:03,100
I think I screwed up last night,
and I need you to help me fix it.

564
00:35:03,524 --> 00:35:04,810
What did you have in mind?

565
00:35:04,978 --> 00:35:07,938
That picture in your office...
That was taken from your building?

566
00:35:15,881 --> 00:35:17,569
Baklava.
You and me.

567
00:35:19,117 --> 00:35:20,441
I've been investigating.

568
00:35:20,566 --> 00:35:22,619
I know where we can find
the best in the city.

569
00:35:22,924 --> 00:35:24,570
To understand
the history of baklava,

570
00:35:24,695 --> 00:35:27,336
you first have to understand
the history of Cyprus,

571
00:35:27,461 --> 00:35:31,361
which is to say the entire narrative
of the Greek-Turkish conflict.

572
00:35:34,299 --> 00:35:37,526
Some heretics will have you believe
that syrup is an authentic topping.

573
00:35:37,651 --> 00:35:39,408
Humbug. Give me honey.

574
00:35:44,703 --> 00:35:46,518
They said it was <i>alfresco</i>.

575
00:35:46,686 --> 00:35:48,222
This isn't a restaurant, Trevor.

576
00:35:48,347 --> 00:35:50,765
No, I... what do you call it?
Google maps'ed it.

577
00:35:52,081 --> 00:35:53,584
Let me go find the manager.

578
00:35:58,198 --> 00:36:01,104
<i>I've been so many places</i>

579
00:36:01,229 --> 00:36:03,246
<i>In my life and time</i>

580
00:36:05,494 --> 00:36:06,997
<i>Sung a lot of songs</i>

581
00:36:09,178 --> 00:36:11,084
<i>And I've made some bad rhymes</i>

582
00:36:20,089 --> 00:36:22,971
<i>I've acted out my love on stages</i>

583
00:36:24,599 --> 00:36:26,934
<i>10,000 people watchin'</i>

584
00:36:28,584 --> 00:36:30,020
<i>We're alone now</i>

585
00:36:30,901 --> 00:36:34,149
<i>And I'm singing this song for you</i>

586
00:36:44,039 --> 00:36:45,244
I was such an idiot.

587
00:36:45,922 --> 00:36:47,172
Yeah, you were.

588
00:37:24,488 --> 00:37:28,340
<i>If I hadn't seen it with my own eyes,
I doubt I would have believed it.</i>

589
00:37:28,465 --> 00:37:31,111
<i>Certainly there was
no magic bow and arrow,</i>

590
00:37:31,236 --> 00:37:33,500
<i>but Trevor created
a romantic scenario</i>

591
00:37:33,625 --> 00:37:36,325
<i>that witnesses would describe
as "magical".</i>

592
00:37:36,793 --> 00:37:39,265
<i>Casebooks are full
of stories about soldiers</i>

593
00:37:39,390 --> 00:37:41,671
<i>who have seen so much suffering
on the battlefield</i>

594
00:37:41,796 --> 00:37:44,445
<i>that the only way they can cope
is to convince themselves</i>

595
00:37:44,570 --> 00:37:47,347
<i>they're Jesus Christ.
The delusion serves</i>

596
00:37:47,515 --> 00:37:49,854
<i>to protect these soldiers'
fragile minds.</i>

597
00:37:49,979 --> 00:37:53,687
<i>I believe my mystery patient
who calls himself Trevor Pierce</i>

598
00:37:53,812 --> 00:37:56,012
<i>has experienced no less a tragedy.</i>

599
00:37:56,137 --> 00:37:59,860
<i>The key to dispelling the delusion,
therefore, is to learn the cause,</i>

600
00:38:00,180 --> 00:38:03,937
<i>treat the heartbreak and allow
this Cupid to find his Psyche.</i>

601
00:38:04,622 --> 00:38:06,033
All right, later!

602
00:38:09,443 --> 00:38:10,495
Dave O'leary?

603
00:38:11,750 --> 00:38:15,000
I'm agent Morris, immigration
and customs enforcement.

604
00:38:15,125 --> 00:38:17,044
I'm afraid I'm gonna need you
to come with me.

605
00:38:17,591 --> 00:38:20,441
Nice story about you
in the paper, by the way.

606
00:38:25,573 --> 00:38:27,673
Hey, boss.
What's the good word?

607
00:38:29,653 --> 00:38:30,849
That singer Dave called.

608
00:38:31,383 --> 00:38:33,884
He was hoping you'd be around.
Immigration caught up with him,

609
00:38:34,009 --> 00:38:36,146
and they put him
on a plane back to Dublin.

610
00:38:37,458 --> 00:38:40,841
He wanted me to tell you thanks
for everything and say good-bye.

611
00:38:41,569 --> 00:38:43,111
You might want to get a cell phone.

612
00:38:56,407 --> 00:38:59,220
I missed his call.
I didn't even get to say good-bye.

613
00:38:59,345 --> 00:39:03,345
I was reading <i>Modern Invention</i>.
There's this riveting piece in there.

614
00:39:03,474 --> 00:39:06,593
Apparently, there are
these flying contraptions now

615
00:39:06,761 --> 00:39:09,769
that allow passengers
to travel great distances.

616
00:39:09,894 --> 00:39:12,557
I have a life here, a job.
I can't just pick up.

617
00:39:13,033 --> 00:39:14,643
True love crosses oceans.

618
00:39:15,020 --> 00:39:18,395
Haven't you heard, Trevor?
People don't fall in love in two days.

619
00:39:19,044 --> 00:39:20,837
See, that's where we're different.

620
00:39:20,962 --> 00:39:24,695
You take your advice from Dr. McCrae.
I take my advice from captain Kirk.

621
00:39:25,358 --> 00:39:26,358
I can't.

622
00:39:26,483 --> 00:39:29,306
I can't put myself
out there like that.

623
00:39:30,076 --> 00:39:31,383
That's how you get hurt.

624
00:39:34,106 --> 00:39:35,356
Okay, I get it.

625
00:39:37,144 --> 00:39:39,418
I got a phone now.
Don't be a stranger.

626
00:39:39,586 --> 00:39:40,586
I won't.

627
00:39:41,733 --> 00:39:42,504
Be good.

628
00:39:46,642 --> 00:39:49,550
<i>It was all I could do to not throw her
over my shoulder and put her on a plane.</i>

629
00:39:49,675 --> 00:39:51,325
<i>I'm pleased you didn't.</i>

630
00:39:52,312 --> 00:39:55,362
<i>I had one card left to play.
No idea if it worked.</i>

631
00:39:58,936 --> 00:40:01,314
Why do mortals make
falling in love so difficult?

632
00:40:01,651 --> 00:40:03,275
You'll get used to it, Trevor.

633
00:40:04,330 --> 00:40:06,971
<i>"Be bold."
What was I thinking?</i>

634
00:40:09,211 --> 00:40:11,514
There's someone
for everyone, Trevor.

635
00:40:11,639 --> 00:40:14,383
You say that
with your authoritative tone.

636
00:40:15,011 --> 00:40:16,811
Even though I know better,

637
00:40:17,369 --> 00:40:18,582
I almost believe you.

638
00:40:18,948 --> 00:40:21,376
Someone broke your heart.
I'm sure of that much.

639
00:40:22,122 --> 00:40:25,380
But you'll heal.
You'll even fall in love again.

640
00:40:25,548 --> 00:40:28,175
Here, with a mortal?
Not likely.

641
00:40:28,343 --> 00:40:30,552
Cupid fell in love with Psyche.
She was a mortal.

642
00:40:30,720 --> 00:40:32,262
I told you, that never happened.

643
00:40:32,770 --> 00:40:34,920
<i>And I never did get that baklava.</i>

644
00:40:35,433 --> 00:40:37,392
You ever hear of this place...
St. Nick's?

645
00:40:37,645 --> 00:40:39,811
Greek place in Soho.
People rave.

646
00:40:40,672 --> 00:40:42,689
Let's have lunch tomorrow.
You and me. I'll buy.

647
00:40:43,260 --> 00:40:44,960
There are rules, Trevor.

648
00:40:45,276 --> 00:40:47,376
Doctor, patient.
Lest I forget.

649
00:40:49,709 --> 00:40:50,697
Here's the thing.

650
00:40:50,865 --> 00:40:53,765
<i>I could really use
some counseling, Dr. McCrae.</i>

651
00:40:54,431 --> 00:40:56,681
Suddenly doubting your omniscience?

652
00:40:57,972 --> 00:41:00,582
But from what people tell me,
you're the best shrink around.

653
00:41:00,750 --> 00:41:02,777
It might take a little time, but...

654
00:41:03,809 --> 00:41:06,288
And with
around-the-clock availability,

655
00:41:06,413 --> 00:41:07,813
some elbow grease,

656
00:41:08,509 --> 00:41:10,383
you might actually be able
to cure me of this.

657
00:41:10,742 --> 00:41:11,593
This what?

658
00:41:12,396 --> 00:41:13,428
Homesickness.

659
00:41:15,408 --> 00:41:16,558
<i>Homesickness?</i>

660
00:41:17,189 --> 00:41:20,268
All right, I will meet you down there,
see if we can't make this work.

661
00:41:21,870 --> 00:41:25,107
- Do you know where we're goin'?
- No earthly idea.

662
00:41:28,361 --> 00:41:32,011
<i>It's on 2nd between Pacific
and Atlantic. How does 1:00 sound?</i>

663
00:41:57,069 --> 00:41:58,769
- I'll be there.
- Bye.

